  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**  \nThe article \"Guerrilla Types in TypeScript\" argues for balancing explicitness and reusability in type design through three techniques to achieve consistent, predictable interfaces. It critiques traditional approaches (single large objects vs. fragmented named types) and introduces strategies like deriving sub-types from primary types (\"Why not all\"), composing logical objects with Mix-ins, and organizing types via Namespaces. Targeting TypeScript developers, the tone is analytical and tutorial, emphasizing practical code examples and metaphors like \"Guerrilla\" to frame quick, effective solutions. Key themes include avoiding naming inconsistencies, leveraging unions for type variants, and improving developer experience through structured type hierarchies.",
